    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1907-02-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1907-02-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="469"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d469">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 871/9.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Jackson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-02-22">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 22, 1907</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 508 Greek Series.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to my dispatch No. 483, of December 15
                    last, I have the honor to report that the Cretan National Assembly met yesterday
                    to receive the announcement of the high commissioner to the effect that the new
                    constitution had been approved by the protecting powers. Mr. Zaimis thereupon
                    took the required oath of office and the assembly adjourned. It is understood
                    that the Cretan cabinet will now resign and that a provisional ministry will be
                    formed to carry on the Government until after the elections, which are to take
                    place in May, and the meeting of the assembly—elected under the new
                    constitution—on July 14, old style.</p>
                <p>For the present quiet prevails in the island, and the process of assimilating it
                    to the Kingdom of Greece is steadily going on. The gendarmerie seems to be doing
                    satisfactorily under its Greek officers, and recently three Greek judges were
                    appointed to the Cretan “Cour d’Appel.”</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John B. Jackson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
